issue.title: [5302] Conditionally Display Inactive Donation Sites on Edit
issue.body: Resolves #5302 ### Description This PR addresses an issue on donation site edit, where once-active donation sites were not appearing in the donation site dropdown after deactivation. This meant that when a user would go back to edit the donation, the donation would no longer be listed in the dropdown, even though it had initially been the selected donation site prior to deactivation. This PR ensures that an inactive donation site is shown in the donation site dropdown on edit, if and only if, the donation site had previously been selected (prior to deactivation). When creating a new donation site, or editing a donation site that did not have the inactive donation site set prior to deactivation, the inactive donation site is _not_ displayed in the dropdow. This PR also adds tests for the change. ### Type of change * Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue) ### How Has This Been Tested? #### To test this change, please do the following: ##### When the donation site has previously been selected, but is then deactivated: - Create a new donation with a donation site. - Then, navigate to "Community" -> "Donation sites" and deactivate the donation site you chose for the new donation. - Navigate back to the donation you created and edit it. - Ensure that the now inactive donation site is accessible from the donation site dropdown. ##### When editing an existing donation site that did not previously select the now-inactive donation site: - Navigate to the donation list and select an unrelated donation that did not previously select the now-inactive donation site. - Ensure that the inactive donation is not displayed in the list of possible donation sites. ##### When creating a new donation: - Create a new donation. - Ensure that the inactive donation is not displayed in the list of possible donation sites. ### Screenshots #### When the donation site has previously been selected, but is then deactivated, it shows on the donation edit page: #### When creating a new donation, the inactive donation site is not displayed in the list of possible donation sites: #### When editing an existing donation site that did not previously select the now-inactive donation site, the inactive donation site is not displayed in the list of possible donation sites:

performed_via_github_app.description:
## Why another GitHub app?
While CI tools can run test on every pull request when it's opened, and on every branch after it's pushed, it may not be sufficient to avoid broken builds.

For instance, if you have two pull requests that modify dependent code, the tests could pass on each pull request independently and Github would allow the merge but the build may break after the merge.

You may configure Github to block pull request that is not up-to-date with master to avoid this issue. But this may not scale with your team. This configuration means every individual engineer has to:

Update current branch with master.
- Wait for the test to pass again.
- Merge the pull request when it's done.
- In case another pull request is merged before that, repeat the steps above.

## How it works
1. Aviator's MergeQueue monitors all pull requests on your Github repository
2. Instead of manually merging pull requests, the engineers label them when ready.
3. MergeQueue prioritizes ready PRs based on FIFO.
4. Based on your configuration, Aviator performs some operations on PRs.
5. Merges PR when all the merge criteria has been met.
6. Reports and dequeues pull requests that fail the criteria.
